	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Pacific island nations seek more benefits from tuna </h1>

			
			<h4>
												26 February 2009
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The eight countries that are parties to the Nauru Agreement (PNA) are to try to gain a greater share of the US$3 billion regional tuna industry, according to an official; they currently get less than 5%. ‘The divide-and-conquer tactics used by companies and countries in negotiating licence agreements have in the past led to little financial return for the island nations’, he stated. Moreover, he feels that ‘The current level of tuna fishing is ‘not sustainable, equitable or beneficial to Pacific islands’.</p><p>The PNA want to forge a joint approach to issuing fishing licences and sustainable tuna fishing. The two key issues are overfishing of yellowfin and bigeye tuna and obtaining more than licensing revenue from the fishing industry. Most of the islands are poor with high unemployment rates and want help in developing domestic fishing fleets, on-shore maintenance facilities, and processing plants.</p><p>Action by the PNA has been catalytic in the agreement to reduce yellowfin and bigeye tuna catches taken by the regional organisation WCPFC, as well as the closure of high seas ‘pockets’ between the 200-mile zones of several islands. ‘We established as a condition of in-zone licensing that fishing nations cannot fish in these pockets,’’ he said ‘If they don’t agree, we won’t give them a license.’</p><p>He emphasised that distant-water fishing nations should not take this as a negative message. ‘Our intention is to work together for our mutual benefit … The message to fishing nations is help us develop our resource and get the benefits … it is ‘an open invitation to distant-water fishing nations, not a threat.’</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
‘Pacific island nations seek more returns from tuna’, <i>Easy Bourse</i>, January 30th 2009<br/>
<a href="http://www.easybourse.com/bourse-actualite/marches/pacific-island-nations-seek-more-returns-from-tuna-606764?PHPSESSID=a9cde230f649792043ff543e33e5a6fe" target="_self">http://www.easybourse.com/bourse-actualite/marches/pacific-island-nation...</a></p><p>
Press article, <i>Marianas Variety News</i>, January 30th 2009<br/>
<a href="http://www.mvarietynews.com/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=14356:pacific-tuna-to-cost-fishing-nations-more&amp;catid=3:pacific-islands&amp;Itemid=43" target="_self">http://www.mvarietynews.com/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=articl...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>EU tuna fleets’ presence in Pacific waters is somewhat limited. But, as ‘sustainability’ and ‘equity’ are at the heart of both EU commitments and Pacific ACP demands, it may be of interest to see how EU-Pacific ACP relations accommodate these. Sustainability of the tuna exploitation is discussed mainly through RFMOs. Unfortunately, these fora have tended to ignore most of the scientific recommendations on tuna conservation. The willingness of the EU to strengthen RFMOs and to support the active participation of ACP in these may be a first step in the right direction. </p><p>In terms of equity, it is not only the licence fees which should be considered, but also investments, protection of the local industry, global sourcing for export to the EU markets, etc. These can be addressed through FPAs and EPAs, where more than ever, it is important to ensure the coherence and coordination between these various components of EU-ACP fisheries relations.</p>
		</div>
		
